data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler introduces new implicit conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>`. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**.

Span-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime (typically an `InvalidOperationException` or `NotSupportedException`).

## How to fix

Force the compiler to pick the LINQ overload by making the receiver `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 3: call Enumerable.Contains directly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three approaches ensure the expression tree references `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable and works with `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`. The same fix applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (which now resolves to the in-place `Span` version).
